{"actual_usd":0.126205,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":255,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"I don't think those explanations carry the weight they need to.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat breathes steady against my shins.* \"Grief can do strange things to a person, yes. But grief-visions don't usually give you a whole stubborn movement of people suddenly acting like death itself lost an argument.\"\n\n*I tuck a loose gray-streaked strand behind my ear.* \"And the 'maybe he didn't die' idea always feels thinner the longer you hold it. A man half-dead, torn open, somehow slipping a guarded tomb, then convincing his friends he'd conquered death proper? That doesn't sound like resurrection. That sounds like a very sick man who ought to be laid down and tended.\"\n\n\"I suppose the real hinge is this: if God raised Jesus, the accounts make the most sense all at once. If you rule that out at the door, then you can piece together other stories...\" *I give a small shrug.* \"But to me they read like substitute dough — you can force it into the pan, but it won't rise the same.\"\n\n\"What part presses on you most — whether miracles can happen at all, or whether these particular witnesses are trustworthy?\"","rolling_24h_usd":83.53188,"run_id":"8047bc33-86a1-4248-afea-9a718d086359"}
